At this point, the greater threat is domestic terrorism. In part this is because there are legal strictures against collecting information on US persons. But for a pair (or greater) foreign nationals to perpetrate such an act, they would have to be in or get into the US without a substantial record that would disqualify them. They would then have to plan and scout out the attack site, acquire the weapons or materials -- all without raising suspicion. Post 9-11, I don't see this as an easy feat.

Russia seems to be following similar patterns to terrorist states; FSB analysts demonstrated Russia's economy will only last until June before collapse; expect Fringe pro Russian entities within America to react before June.
Passage of time decay - underlying factors mentioned in previous forecast (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1377818) stand, did not find anything new to update on.
Unlikely (because generally quite safe, and question quite specific (foreign inspired, >4 dead)). But world getting nastier.
Most of US terrorist attacks have been from people living here. Unlikely.

Weren't the Boston Marathon bombings committed by US citizens!? Anyway, the odds are clearly not zero, but foreign interference currently seems more interested in inspiring US citizens to kill each other than to waste their time on an in person attack.

FTOs will not be as likely of a threat this year as the movement that inspired them is more focused on regional issues in the general CENTCOM geography. There is always a chance that a lone-wolf, FTO inspired attack could easily cause five fatalities however--especially given Americans' access to weapons. So at any given day before 1 Sep, there's a distinct possibility. Domestic terror in this year is much more likely.

If I am counting correctly, 4 events since 1990 qualify under these criteria - 1993 WTC, 9/11, 2013 Boston, and 2015 San Bernardino. Discounting earlier years due to minimal relevance (massively reduced international communications, change in the nature of terrorism, etc.), we get a base rate of (4/31)*(8/12) = 8,6%, hovering near the crowd consensus.
Some are always plotting. I shouldn't keep my forecast too low just because there wasn't one recently. The FBI is amazing, but some do get through.

We are onshoring this activity and have no need of outside assistance. If I were foreign terrorists (full disclosure: I'm not) I wouldn't bother. No matter how many people I managed to kill, the story would get lost within a week by the next domestic effort.

There are essentially some things that lead me to believe the possibility is very low: *A CCTA, with multiple actors as a defining feature, is in itself a rare event in the United States. In the last ten years I think San Bernadino is the only one I think can be said to fit the bill (as stated above). *Many attacks that are labled terrorist attacks are domestic, not foreign, and this seems to exclude a lot of possibilities. *At last five fatalities raises the bar as well, although admittedly perhaps not if it is already established that we're talking about CCTAs.

The rate of CCTA killing more than 10 in the US currently stands at 0.05 per year since 9/11 (bear in mind a CCTA requires multiple perpetrators so only San Bernadino meets the strict criteria here). So my base for this (roughly) 12 month period is 5%. A recent development worth considering is the fall of Afghanistan to the taliban thus providing a potential safe haven. However, this most likely be an issue in this timeframe as it would have to be planned and executed in less than 12 months.

I don't think there will be a CCTA in US. First the US is more and more withdrawing from the world stage, which makes less likely to be targeted by FTOs. And I also get the impression, that various islamist groups and governments are (at the moment) more fighting each other, than some foreign powers which are actively withdrawing. And for domestic perpetrators, which get FTO inspiration, seems to me US law enforcement keeps a close eye on them. But when a FTO inspired CCTA is executed I expect it to be committed more likely by persons already residing in the US. @Hesch: The US and the Taliban have a kind of gentlemen agreement: As long the Taliban are not ploting against the US or hosting anybody who is planning attacks the US is turning basically a blind eye on the Taliban and what they are doing in Afghanistan. Furthermore the Taliban are seeking international recognition, want to build up an economy, secure foreign aid, so ploting attacks against the West or giving shelter to anybody who actually does, not such a good idea for the Taliban if they what achieve any of that, there is too much for them to loose.
I'd have higher estimates as Taliban becomes more established in AFG. I'd be curious to know what the crowds thinks of that at the moment.

Post Afghanistan draw-down, and given the general downward trend in high-profile American international exposure, I assess a significantly lower risk of future attack vs base rates that could be estimated from the past 20-30 years or so. The odds of a successful complex attack—if attempted—are also exceedingly low because of ongoing counter-terror efforts by the government.

Another question is how is the landscape changing? 5.) and quality of sources need to be determined. Primary Findings:

Since the 9/11 attacks, no foreign terrorist organization has successfully directed and carried out a deadly attack inside the United States. The most likely threat to the United States comes from terrorists inspired by a mixture of ideologies including jihadist, far-right, and idiosyncratic strains, radicalized on or via the internet, and taking advantage of the availability of weapons, particularly semi-automatic firearms, in the United States.
Thanks to a discussion with @probahilliby
If the question had said "foreign or domestic terrorist organization" I would put the odds more like 25%.

It will happen, but I am not certain within the allotted timeframe. Our open southern border is allowing people from all over the planet to enter the US unregulated. Whether or not that will be the point of ingress remains to be seen, but it certainly makes it easy for them to get here. I happen to work in the town where the last attack occurred and that actor was a member of a foreign military who was here legally. Regardless of how they get here, they are already inside our borders. It will happen, I am just unsure of their timetable.

I hesitate to forecast this, because how could we possibly know? And we have no access to all the information the FBI, CIA, NSA and others do, about both what individuals or groups are planning and what law enforcement is doing to stop any such plans from coming to fruition. My low forecast is based both on a feeling that there is a generally lower level of hatred directed at the US at the moment by FTOs and their sympathizers and on faith in the tremendous competence and dedication of our law enforcement personnel, who have already prevented so many attacks behind the scenes.
